    {
        "model": "campaign_trail.election",
        "pk": 20,
        "fields": {
            "year": 2016,
            "display_year": "2026 Gorton and Denton By-Election",
            "summary": "<p>With Labour MP Andrew Gwynne announcing his resignation from Parliament, a seat in Manchester opens up. Many have been saying that Andy Burnham, the mayor of Greater Manchester will take the opportunity to enter the House of Commons and position himself to become the next Prime Minister.</p>\n<p>With the incumbent Labour Prime Minister Keir Starmer facing rock-bottom polling and the loss of Runcorn and Helsby last year to Reform UK, his position as Prime Minister looks increasingly shaky day after day.</p>\n<p>With the popular Andy Burnham likely to run in this seat, it's looking like a Labour victory is all but guaranteed, but could he face more obstacles than he bargained for?</p>",
            "image_url": "https://file.garden/Zmvf_kGfBgouz-z5/2026%20Gorton%20and%20Denton/Gorton%20and%20Denton%20Election%20Image.png",
            "winning_electoral_vote_number": 270,
            "advisor_url": "123",
            "recommended_reading": `<div style='overflow-y:scroll;height:370px;margin-bottom:30px;'><h2>April Fools!</h2><h3>But I would like to talk about my future plans for modding.</h3><p>If you're not aware of my work, I'm the creator of 2017 UK and 2016 Brexit. After getting burnt out on working on 2017 UK, I needed a breath of fresh air, and decided that this 2026 by-election in the Gorton and Denton constituency may have been one of the most interesting I've lived through in my lifetime. As such, I saw someone make a passing comment about turning it into a mod, and from there, I decided to do it for real. That's right, my next project is the 2026 Gorton and Denton by-election.</p><h3>Why this election in specific?</h3><p>A couple of reasons, but the main one is it's a less complex scenario to faithfully execute. I'm not comfortable with an unfaithful adaptation of a historical campaign. It's why I went the whole way with 2017 UK, simulating all 650 constituencies and every party that won a seat in that election, including the Northern Ireland parties, even though their influence by the main environment over in Great Britain is limited. The resulting mod was immensely large, actually I don't think anything by that point had as many as 650 different states. For that reason, switching focus to working on another UK general election just would run into the same problems. The mod would get bloated and it would quickly become tedious to work on. That's why I opted for a simpler project. There are two ways to simplify. The first is to reduce the number of parties. That was the motivation behind 2016 Brexit. Looking back at it, it's not the best mod, it was my first time ever working with CYOA, I've learnt a lot about how that works since. The other method of simplification is to reduce the number of states/constituencies. That's where the Gorton and Denton by-election comes in. This map only has seven electoral regions, known specifically as wards. In return, this by-election still simulates all 12 candidates that ran in it.<p>I could understand if you're disappointed that this is my next project, and that I've put the development of 2017 UK on hold, maybe it's disappointment about me not tackling another one of my country's many general elections, or maybe you're curious, perhaps you want to know more about this little window into 2026 UK politics, since it is very deep with a lot happening, especially surrounding the Royal Family and UK Government's problematic connections with Jeffrey Epstein, as more of the Epstein files are released, and their reaction to it, and how much that likely had an impact (though not exclusively) in shaping the way this by-election unfolded. For a by-election, we know a surprising amount about it.</p><h3>How far are you into it so far? When can we expect a release?</h3><p>So far, the Labour campaign has been written fully, and writing has started on Reform UK's campaign. The Green Party will also be playable with a full campaign, yet that hasn't yet started production. The plan ideally would be to recruit a team of writers that are able to maintain motivation to work on the project whilst I can turn my attention towards the coding side of things, with minimal focus on writing myself. This would ultimately be the ideal situation for me to be in, though it's not looking like that will be completely the case, and so I've found myself doing a good chunk of the writing as well.</p><p>As for a release date? I can't promise anything yet, though I would like to aim for completion by mid May, and ideally earlier than that, but that all depends on how well the mod creation progress goes, most especially writing, since creative tasks like that are a lot more unpredictable than tasks that require less creativity like coding. It all depends on when I, or the other writers have the inspiration to sit down and bang out some lines. So far, consider the writing for the whole mod (all three campaigns) about 35% to 40% done. Labour is likely going to be the most writing-intensive of the three, since it has to factor in two candidates, the others only have to have one. But, the writing of Labour is complete, as previously mentioned.</p>`,
